  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Prevention and Control of Leishmaniasis in North-West Syria</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In order to address the high burden of leishmaniasis across northern Syria, the MENTOR Initiative will respond to the 2020 HRP Strategic Objective 1 &#x201C;Provide life-saving humanitarian assistance to the most vulnerable people with an emphasis on those in areas with high severity of needs&#x201D; and the SCHF Allocation Strategic Objective 2 (ASO2) &#x201C;Life-saving humanitarian assistance and protection to the most vulnerable people with an emphasis on underserved areas with high severity of needs&#x201D; through providing services that protect people from leishmaniasis in Syria, a disease which has progressed to epidemic proportions in the last years. 

MENTOR proposes to implement the following activities:

1. Prevention of Visceral (VL) and Cutaneous Leishmaniasis (CL) transmission in a multitude of communities. MENTOR proposes to provide protection from sandfly bites and subsequent disease to 265,506 households / 1,539,942 beneficiaries through an Indoor Residual Spraying campaign (IRS) in areas of high leishmaniasis incidence. 

2. Information about leishmaniasis and its transmission to empower communities to protect themselves from leishmaniasis infection and disease. MENTOR will run a combined Information, Education and Communication / Behaviour Change Communication Campaign (IEC/BCC) to ensure households are empowered to prevent leishmaniasis transmission within their household/shelter. This will be done by various methods and delivery strategies, such as outreach activities, health sessions and training of community leaders, to maximise uptake and correct utilization of leishmaniasis prevention and case management services.

In addition to a large-scale IRS campaign in 2022, this proposal also includes a response to the high incidence of leishmaniasis in Atmeh, which will be an IRS campaign in 2021, targeting 200,000 Internally Displaced People.</narrative>
  </description>
